We call it “Yoga for Runners.” My physio calls it “a cry for help.” 😁

From TyingShoelaceasana to SadDownwardDog, our post-run “yoga” is sweaty, chaotic, and completely unintentional.

But hey, balance is balance… even if it comes with cramps and GPS stress.😉

🎥 Featuring @runwithchristine, who runs like the wind while I pretend to breathe like a yogi

If you’ve ever cursed mid-run and called it “pranayama”… this one’s for you 😌
👇Tag your running buddy who desperately needs a yoga mat!!

P.s. Watch till the end as I slid in a cheeky remark for our British friends 😉

71 and still chasing finish lines - and joy. 🏃‍♀️✨⁠

In this rapid fire, @runwithchristine gets real with @thedefaultrunner on running, reinvention and why it’s never too late to start.⁠
⁠
No flex. No filters. Just the good stuff.⁠
⁠
Catch them live at @tracktalk.delhincr - June 22, 3PM, India International Centre.

Free to attend. Link in bio.

At 71, Christine Pemberton (@runwithchristine) is proof that it’s never too late to start running — or living fully. She ran her first race at 60, driven not by competition, but by curiosity. Since then, she’s ticked off one bucket list dream after another: running races with a real bib number, appearing in a Bollywood film (Bhaag Milkha Bhaag), being interviewed by the BBC, and finishing half marathons across cities and countries she once only read about.

But her story didn’t begin with running. Over 40 years ago, while waiting for a delayed Indian Airlines flight in Bombay, she met Himmat Sher Singh Kalsia — the stranger who would become her husband. That serendipitous moment changed everything. She moved from England to India and eventually made Delhi her home.

Now, she runs not just for fitness, but for joy, discovery, and the thrill of doing things she once thought impossible.

Join @thedefaultrunner in conversation with Christine at TrackTalk on 22nd June 2025, from 3:30 PM to 6:30 PM at the India International Centre, Lodhi Gardens, New Delhi.

🎟️ Free Entry – Register via link in bio

Together, they’ll talk about aging with strength, staying open to new beginnings and why the real finish line is always internal.

Christine Pemberton (@runwithchristine) started running at 60. She’s 71 now and still going strong.

Originally from England, she’s been living (and running) in Delhi for 10+ years. She’s not here to prove anything - just to show what’s possible when you start, stay curious and keep showing up.

Catch her at @tracktalk.delhincr on June 22, India International Centre, at 3 pm.

YES!!!! 💪🏻

70kg today after almost 2 years 💪🏻

And all thanks to @koach_karan who has patiently coached me, adjusting training for my travels + silly niggles + yet more silly niggles 🙏🏻

Last lifted 70kg just before I turned 70, so now I need to add on a couple more kg before my next birthday 😊

It felt SO good!

An epic climb on Chulu Far East.

Snow conditions stopped us 250 metres from the summit. Freezing winds, numbing cold, but views to cherish forever.

More anon, but for now we are warm & snug in a tea house & happily reliving our adventures.

The usual flawless organisation from @whitemagicadventure @sherpa7382 @ngawang295 

Great company from my fellow climbers @gvoninsta @gagan_paul26

latestPosts.caption:
It’s Easter weekend, & today, Good Friday, I’m in one of the most spiritual places I know, #boudanath.

I circumnamulated this beautiful stupa, spinning the hundreds of prayer wheels, surrounded by devout Tibetan Buddhists.

Chatted to a Chinese lady who was thrilled that I live in India (“The Buddha’s  birthplace. You are so lucky.”) She recommended a book written by a Vietnamese author (“Apart from language text books, this is the first book in English I have ever read. It’s taken me 3 months & I’m not finished.”)

Talk about the community of nations ❤️

Have a blessed Easter, my friends.

#Nepal #kathmandu #easter #goodfriday
